eous deviations from general\nrelativity. To address these issues and be ready to reap the scientific\nbenefits of 3G GW detectors in the 2030s, waveform models that are\nsignificantly more physically complete and accurate need to be developed in the\nnext decade along with major advances in efficiency and accuracy of NR codes.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 20 Dec 2019 19:00:16 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-12-24"}
{"id":"1912.10056","submitter":"Mirjam Weilenmann","authors":"Mirjam Weilenmann, Benjamin Dive, David Trillo, Edgar A. Aguilar,\n  Miguel Navascu\\'es","title":"Entanglement Detection Beyond Measuring Fidelities","comments":"5+3 pages, 2 figures, 1 table. Supplemented with GitHub repository.\n  v2: improved presentation (including new appendices that give additional\n  technical details). v3: corrected errors in Table I","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. Lett. 124, 200502 (2020)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevLett.124.200502","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  One of the most widespread methods to determine if a quantum state is\nentangled, or to quantify its entanglement dimensionality, is by measuring its\nfidelity with respect to a pure state. In this Letter we find a large class of\nstates whose entanglement cannot be detected in this manner; we call them\nunfaithful. We find that unfaithful states are ubiquitous in information\ntheory. For small dimensions, we check numerically that most bipartite states\nare both entangled and unfaithful. Similarly, numerical searches in low\ndimensions show that most pure entangled states remain entangled but become\nunfaithful when a certain amount of white noise is added. We also find that\nfaithfulness can be self-activated, i.e., there exist instances of unfaithful\nstates whose tensor powers are faithful. To explore how the fidelity approach\nlimits the quantification of entanglement dimensionality, we generalize the\nnotion of an unfaithful state to that of a D-unfaithful state, one that cannot\nbe certified as D-dimensionally entangled by measuring its fidelity with\nrespect to a pure state. For describing such states, we additionally introduce\na hierarchy of semidefinite programming relaxations that fully characterizes\nthe set of states of Schmidt rank at most D.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 20 Dec 2019 19:01:07 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 27 Apr 2020 07:53:59 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Thu, 13 Aug 2020 12:27:29 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-08-14"}
